---
import Layout from "../../../../layouts/index.astro"
import Editor from "../../../../components/Editor/index.astro"
import getExampleCode from "../../../../utilities/getExampleCode"
import getMarkdownFromCode from "../../../../utilities/getMarkdownFromCode"
import * as divide from "../../../../../lib/calculations/operators/constructors/Divide?raw"

const glob1 = import.meta.glob("../../../../examples/calculations/*", {
	query: "?raw",
	import: "default",
})

const glob2 = import.meta.glob("../../../../examples/calculations/divide/*", {
	query: "?raw",
	import: "default",
})

const { css, html, js } = await getExampleCode({ ...glob1, ...glob2 })

const frag1 = await getMarkdownFromCode(divide)
const frag2 = await getMarkdownFromCode(
	"const divide = operation => (arg? => Either<Array<Error>, result>)",
)
---

<Layout>
	<p>
		<code>Divide</code> is a curried constructor used to create a JS/JSON configuration
		object that represents a <strong>division operation</strong>.
	</p>
	<Fragment set:html={frag1} />
	<p>
		The first parameter to <code>Divide</code> determines the datatype of the return
		value of the division operation: <code>Number</code> (float) or <code
			>Integer</code
		>.
	</p>
	<p>
		The second parameter is the <code>dividend</code>; the third is the <code
			>divisor</code
		>. Both are <strong>operations</strong>, which must eventually evaluate to
		values. The divisor will eventually be divided into the dividend to produce
		the <strong>quotient</strong> (result).
	</p>
	<p>
		The dividend and divisor operations (multiply, subtract, etc.) may be nested
		to any depth, but the bottom (leaf) nodes <strong>must return values</strong
		>. Values are injected with <a href="../../../injectors">injectors</a>.
	</p>
	<p>
		Because <code>Divide</code> is curried, we can simplify our code by partial application,
		for example,
		<code>const Quotient = Divide("Integer")</code>. This returns a function
		that takes the dividend and divisor operations and returns a Divide
		configuration for working with integers.
	</p>
	<p>See below for an example.</p>
	<h2>The <code>divide</code> function</h2>
	<p>
		We pass our configuration object to <a
			href="/calculations/composers/composeOperators"
			><code>composeOperators</code></a
		>, which composes the operations and returns a single function. This
		function takes an optional argument and returns the result of the
		calculation as a Right, e.g., <code>&lbrace; right: 42 &rbrace;</code>, or a
		Left with an array of <a href="/constructors/error"><code>Error</code></a> objects,
		<code>&lbrace; left: [Error] &rbrace;</code>.
	</p>
	<Fragment set:html={frag2} />
	<p>
		<code>composeOperators</code> works by recursing down through the
		<code>operation</code> object, calling the correct operator function based on
		the <code>tag</code>, and composing the functions returned. <code
			>composeOperators</code
		> then returns this composed function. See <a
			href="/calculations/composers/composeOperators"
			><code>composeOperators</code></a
		> for a more detailed explanation.
	</p>
	<p>
		The injectors are not called until this composed <code>calculate</code> function
		is run. Hence, evaluation is lazy: the values are not injected until the last
		moment.
	</p>
	<p>
		See the <a href="/injectors">injectors</a> for a complete list of how values
		may be injected. See the <a href="/calculations/operators"
			>list of operators</a
		>
		for the full range of available mathematical operations.
		<h2>Example</h2>
		<p>
			We use <a href="/calculations/composers/composeOperators"
				><code>composeOperators</code></a
			> to create a <code>calculate</code> function. We call the <code
				>calculate</code
			> function and pass it an (optional) argument to run our operation and calculate
			the quotient.
		</p>
		<p>
			Here our dividend operation is a nested multiplication operation of three
			constants (using <a href="/injectors/constant"><code>Constant</code></a>).
			Our divisor is also an operation that returns the argument passed to the
			composed function (using <a href="/injectors/fromArgument"
				><code>FromArgument</code></a
			>).
		</p>
		<p>Try leaving one of the numbers undefined to see an Error returned.</p>
		<Editor
			{css}
			{html}
			{js}
		/>
	</p>
</Layout>
